{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17414020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17414020"},"attributes":{"position":30,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:36:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:36:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490945"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:24:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/778"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.14,0.05,0.05,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/778"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82833"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"2798"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45055"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of a swelling on her neck. She is otherwise asymptomatic and well. On examination, the swelling is 3 cm in diameter and appears to arise from the right lobe of the thyroid. The left lobe appears normal, and there is no evidence of lymph node enlargement. Ultrasound confirms the presence of an isolated solid nodule, and the rest of the gland appears normal. Fine needle aspiration cytology reveals atypia of undetermined significance. Thyroid function tests are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat ultrasound in the next 6-12 months","CT neck and chest","MRI neck and chest","Radiofrequency ablation","Diagnostic right lobectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the fine needle aspiration (FNA) cytology reveals atypia of undetermined significance, which carries a 5-15% risk of malignancy. The most appropriate management is to monitor the nodule with a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat ultrasound in the next 6-12 months\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows for assessment of any changes in size or characteristics that might warrant further investigation or intervention. If there is more than or equal to a 50% increase in nodule volume in this time, a further FNA would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical removal (either hemithyroidectomy or total thyroidectomy)\u003C/strong\u003E of the nodule is not indicated from a medical perspective. If a nodule is large (\u0026gt;4cm) there may be an argument for surgical removal, but this is not the case here as hers is only 3cm. There are less invasive options available if it were to be removed, hence surgery can be avoided in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT neck and chest\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI neck and chest\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated at this stage, as these imaging modalities are typically reserved for cases with suspected locally advanced disease or metastasis, which is not suggested by the current findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is a minimally invasive procedure used for benign thyroid nodules, but it is not commonly used and is not indicated in this scenario without further evidence of malignancy or significant symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic right lobectomy\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered if there is significant growth or if the patient prefers surgical intervention over a \u0027watch and wait\u0027 approach. However, it is not the immediate next step given the current findings and the absence of symptoms or significant risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atypia of undetermined significance on fine needle aspiration of a thyroid nodule has a 5-15% risk of malignancy.","Thyroid nodules with atypia of undetermined significance often require follow-up with ultrasound and possible repeat biopsy.","Surgical intervention is not immediately indicated for thyroid nodules with atypia of undetermined significance unless there is significant growth or other concerning features."],"references":["Papini E, Rago T, Gambelunghe G, Valcavi R, Bizzarri G, Vitti P, De Feo P, Riganti F, Misischi I, Di Stasio E, Pacella CM. Long-term efficacy of ultrasound-guided laser ablation for benign solid thyroid nodules. Results of a three-year multicenter prospective randomized trial. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Oct;99(10):3653-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25050903/","Muhammad H, Santhanam P, Russell JO. Radiofrequency ablation and thyroid nodules: updated systematic review. Endocrine. 2021 Jun;72(3):619-632. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33449296/","Bailey S \u0026 Wallwork B, 2018. Differentiating between benign and malignant thyroid nodules: An evidence-based approach in general practice. RACGP. Vol 47, Issue 11. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-03-18-4518. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/november/differentiating-between-benign-and-malignant-t-1.","Wong R, Farrell S \u0026 Grossmann M, 2018. Thyroid nodules: diagnosis and management. Medical Journal of Australia. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/system/files/issues/209_02/10.5694mja17.01204.pdf."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82833"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"778"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82833"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"202